<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1902-02-06T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1902-02-06T00:00:00-05:00" n="872" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d872">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">King</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Hay</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Legation of the United States</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Bangkok</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1902-02-06"><hi rend="italic">February 6,
                                1902</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 111.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Is a consular or diplomatic officer who is
                            duly authorized to issue United States passports permitted to issue a
                            passport to a citizen of the United States who is at the time of
                            application residing in the jurisdiction of another official so
                            authorized?</p>
                        <p>The statutes and instructions are not clear on this point, but seem to
                            imply that he is not. Will the Department please interpret?</p>
                        <p>I have, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Hamilton King.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>